WEBVTT

01:21.504 --> 01:27.246
♪ After seven years
Of life upon the ocean ♪

01:27.246 --> 01:32.119
♪ It is time to bid
The seven seas farewell ♪

01:32.119 --> 01:38.191
♪ And the city I’ve pinned
Seven years of hopes on ♪

01:38.191 --> 01:40.490
♪ Lies just over the horizon ♪

01:40.490 --> 01:45.594
♪ I can hear the harbor bell ♪

01:45.594 --> 01:48.069
Land ahoy!

01:52.469 --> 01:57.177
♪ Got a tattered overcoat
And battered suitcase ♪

01:57.177 --> 01:58.178
Au revoir, Chef.

01:58.178 --> 02:01.478
♪ Got a pair of leaky boots
Upon my ♪

02:01.478 --> 02:03.084
- ♪ Feet ♪
- Sorry, Cook!

02:03.084 --> 02:04.646
♪ Gotta drag myself up ♪

02:04.646 --> 02:07.286
♪ By my one good bootlace ♪

02:07.286 --> 02:10.157
♪ Gotta work
My rotten socks off ♪

02:10.157 --> 02:11.554
♪ If I want to make ends meet ♪

02:11.554 --> 02:16.526
♪ I’ve poured everything
I’ve got into my chocolate ♪

02:16.526 --> 02:21.003
♪ Now it’s time
To show the world my recipes ♪

02:21.003 --> 02:21.696
Good luck, Willy!

02:21.696 --> 02:24.699
♪ I’ve got
12 silver sovereigns ♪

02:24.699 --> 02:26.338
♪ In my pocket ♪

02:26.338 --> 02:27.174
Goodbye, Cook!

02:27.174 --> 02:32.179
♪ And a hatful of dreams ♪

02:38.251 --> 02:43.157
♪ There’s a famous restaurant
On every street here ♪

02:43.157 --> 02:46.688
♪ There’s Brandino’s
And the bar Parisienne ♪

02:46.688 --> 02:48.195
Restaurant map, sir?
- Thank you.

02:48.195 --> 02:53.035
♪ Got a little map to tell me
Where to eat here ♪

02:53.035 --> 02:55.400
♪ Had a dozen
Silver sovereigns ♪

02:55.400 --> 02:57.974
♪ Now I’m somehow down to ten ♪

02:57.974 --> 02:59.173
♪ Want the finest produce?♪

02:59.173 --> 03:02.011
- ♪ This is where
They stock it ♪

03:02.011 --> 03:03.111
That’s three sovereigns, mate.

03:03.111 --> 03:06.279
♪ Though the prices
Are suspiciously extreme ♪

03:06.279 --> 03:08.017
Break my pumpkin,
you pay for it.

03:08.017 --> 03:09.018
♪ I’ve got...♪

03:09.018 --> 03:10.613
Five, six, seven...

03:11.581 --> 03:16.157
♪ Six silver sovereigns
In my pocket ♪

03:16.157 --> 03:19.754
♪ And a hatful of dreams ♪

03:19.754 --> 03:22.031
Brush your coat, sir?
No, thank you.

03:22.031 --> 03:25.001
Cologne?
No. Leave me alone.

03:26.266 --> 03:27.465
♪ At last ♪

03:27.465 --> 03:30.336
♪ The Galeries Gourmet ♪

03:30.336 --> 03:35.572
♪ I knew that
We’d see it one day ♪

03:35.572 --> 03:38.113
It’s everything you said,
Mamma.

03:38.113 --> 03:39.675
♪ And oh, so much more ♪

03:39.675 --> 03:45.054
♪ Each way that you turn,
Another famous
Chocolate store ♪

03:45.054 --> 03:46.319
♪ Here’s my destiny ♪

03:46.319 --> 03:49.421
♪ I just need to unlock it ♪

03:49.421 --> 03:51.390
♪ Will I crash and burn ♪

03:51.390 --> 03:54.756
♪ Or go up like a rocket?♪

03:54.756 --> 03:56.692
♪ I got nothing to offer ♪

03:56.692 --> 03:59.695
♪ But my chocolate ♪

03:59.695 --> 04:04.073
♪ And a hatful ♪

04:04.073 --> 04:06.570
♪ Of dreams ♪

04:06.570 --> 04:08.209
Yeah!

04:18.054 --> 04:20.551
No daydreaming.

04:26.359 --> 04:31.331
♪ In this city,
Anyone can be successful ♪

04:31.331 --> 04:36.270
♪ If they’ve talent
And work hard, or so they say ♪

04:36.270 --> 04:41.638
♪ But they didn’t mention
It would be so stressful ♪

04:41.638 --> 04:45.477
♪ Just to make
A dozen silver sovereigns ♪

04:45.477 --> 04:48.216
♪ Last more than a day ♪

04:49.085 --> 04:53.122
Could you spare a sovereign
for a place to sleep, love?

04:53.122 --> 04:54.486
Of course.

04:54.486 --> 04:57.456
Here. Take all you need.

04:57.522 --> 04:58.292
Thank you.

04:58.292 --> 05:04.595
♪ I’ve got one silver sovereign
In my pocket ♪

05:13.373 --> 05:18.213
♪ And a hatful of dreams ♪

05:39.333 --> 05:40.796
Hmm.

05:41.599 --> 05:42.798
There we go.

05:42.798 --> 05:46.142
Time for a little nightcap.

05:51.906 --> 05:53.545
Mm.

05:57.648 --> 05:58.385
Okay.

05:58.385 --> 06:01.586
Hello there. No, stop.
Hey, shoo.

06:01.586 --> 06:03.225
Go away, stop!

06:03.225 --> 06:04.358
Go away, shoo! Shoo!

06:04.358 --> 06:05.656
-  Stop!

06:05.656 --> 06:07.691
- Sit.

06:07.823 --> 06:09.363
Sorry about Tiddles.

06:09.363 --> 06:11.662
Seems to have
an unusual interest

06:11.662 --> 06:13.301
in your legs.

06:13.301 --> 06:14.269
Must be these pants.

06:14.269 --> 06:16.733
I got them
from a mailman in Minsk.

06:16.733 --> 06:18.174
That would be it.

06:18.174 --> 06:19.769
Tiddles would spend all day

06:19.769 --> 06:22.310
pursuing postal workers
if he could.

06:22.310 --> 06:24.279
Wouldn’t you, boy?

06:25.610 --> 06:28.778
You’re not planning on
sleeping there, are you, son?

06:28.778 --> 06:29.812
Oh, it’s just for a night.

06:29.812 --> 06:32.518
By this time tomorrow,
I plan to have
made my fortune.

06:32.518 --> 06:36.522
By this time tomorrow,
you’ll be frozen solid.

06:36.522 --> 06:38.953
Oh, don’t be ridiculous.

06:38.953 --> 06:40.526
Ooh.

06:41.329 --> 06:42.759
Perhaps it is a little cold
for camping.

06:42.759 --> 06:46.763
But unfortunately,
I’m not in a position
to pay for a room, sir.

06:46.763 --> 06:50.206
Oh, I’m sorry to hear that.
- Mmm.

06:50.206 --> 06:51.768
But as luck would have it,

06:51.768 --> 06:55.937
I know someone who might
be able to help you out.

06:56.311 --> 06:56.773
Really?

06:56.773 --> 06:59.380
- Here we are, Mr. Wonka.

06:59.380 --> 07:00.348
Home sweet home.

07:01.778 --> 07:04.451
Get your filthy paws
off my front door,

07:04.451 --> 07:05.650
you mangy mutt.

07:05.650 --> 07:07.586
-  If that’s you,
Bleacher,

07:07.586 --> 07:08.620
you’d better have my gin.

07:08.620 --> 07:12.558
Oh, I have something better
than gin, Mrs. Scrubitt.

07:13.262 --> 07:15.363
A guest.

07:15.363 --> 07:16.331
Hmm.

07:16.331 --> 07:19.598
Oh! Well, why didn’t
you say?

07:19.598 --> 07:20.863
- Come on in, sir.

07:20.863 --> 07:24.669
Welcome to Scrubitt
and Bleacher’s
Guest House and Laundry.

07:24.669 --> 07:28.640
Make yourself at home,
warm your cockles by the fire.

07:28.640 --> 07:30.378
- Gin?
-  Oh.

07:30.378 --> 07:30.840
Noodle!

07:30.840 --> 07:31.907
Yes, Mrs. Scrubitt?

07:31.907 --> 07:34.448
Put that book down
and get our guest
a glass o’ gin.

07:34.448 --> 07:36.351
Poor man’s frozen
half to death.

07:36.351 --> 07:37.385
Thank you, Mrs. Scrubitt.

07:37.385 --> 07:39.849
You and your husband
have been so kind to me.

07:39.849 --> 07:40.850
Husband?

07:40.850 --> 07:42.016
Him?

07:42.016 --> 07:42.951
Husband.

07:42.951 --> 07:44.425
Oh, you’d love that,
wouldn’t ya?

07:44.425 --> 07:46.757
- No.
- Oh, I’m holding out
for someone

07:46.757 --> 07:49.265
far superior
to that idle peasant.

07:49.265 --> 07:52.499
- Chin-chin.

07:52.994 --> 07:56.404
That is
extremely strong stuff.

07:56.404 --> 07:57.702
Yeah, you can
run cars on that.

07:57.702 --> 08:00.837
So, what is it I can do
for you? Room, is it?

08:00.837 --> 08:02.740
Well, yes, but, uh...

08:02.740 --> 08:07.008
Mr. Wonka is temporarily
embarrassed.

08:07.008 --> 08:08.845
Oh, no. You don’t say.

08:08.845 --> 08:11.353
I’m afraid that’s true,
Mrs. Scrubitt.

08:11.353 --> 08:11.848
But...

08:11.848 --> 08:13.916
all that’s about to change.
- Oh, yeah?

08:13.916 --> 08:16.050
You see,
I’m something of a magician,

08:16.050 --> 08:17.689
inventor and chocolate maker.

08:17.689 --> 08:19.724
And first thing tomorrow
at the Galeries Gourmet,

08:19.724 --> 08:23.398
I plan to unveil
my most astonishing
creation yet.

08:23.398 --> 08:25.994
- Oh?
- Prepare to be amazed

08:25.994 --> 08:28.304
as I present to you...

08:29.569 --> 08:30.438
A teapot?

08:30.438 --> 08:31.967
No, that’s just
for making tea.

08:31.967 --> 08:34.673
- One second.

08:35.443 --> 08:37.874
That’s for my stew.

08:37.874 --> 08:39.348
It’s in here somewhere.

08:39.348 --> 08:42.417
Don’t you worry, Mr. Wonka.
I can see you’re a man
of great ingenuity.

08:42.417 --> 08:44.518
And we’ve got
just the thing for ya.

08:44.518 --> 08:45.849
The entrepreneurial package.

08:45.849 --> 08:47.455
Now, the room
is one sovereign a night,

08:47.455 --> 08:48.984
but you don’t have to pay
till 6:00 tomorrow.

08:48.984 --> 08:51.525
Does that give you enough time
to earn a few pennies?

08:51.525 --> 08:53.989
More than enough,
Mrs. Scrubitt.

08:53.989 --> 08:54.792
Thank you.

08:54.792 --> 08:57.630
Oh, it’s the least I can do
for a stranger in need.

08:57.630 --> 09:00.534
Now, sign here
and we’re all done.

09:00.534 --> 09:03.966
- All righty.

09:05.066 --> 09:08.102
Read the small print.

09:08.377 --> 09:08.872
What?

09:08.872 --> 09:11.611
Thank you, Noodle.
That’ll do.

09:11.611 --> 09:12.843
Ooh. What’d she say?

09:12.843 --> 09:14.042
Who’s that, then?
- The girl.

09:14.042 --> 09:15.780
What girl?
- That girl.
It sounded like,

09:15.780 --> 09:20.851
"Read the small print."
And there does seem
to be a lot of...

09:20.851 --> 09:23.986
Oh. Oh. Oh.

09:24.118 --> 09:26.021
Oh. Oh.

09:26.021 --> 09:27.891
Oh. Just keeps on coming.

09:27.891 --> 09:30.597
Yeah, you don’t wanna listen
to Noodle, Mr. Wonka.

09:30.597 --> 09:32.797
She’s damaged.
- Damaged?

09:32.797 --> 09:34.128
Orphan Syndrome.

09:34.128 --> 09:35.470
Orphan Syndrome?

09:35.470 --> 09:37.538
Orphan Syndrome.

09:37.538 --> 09:40.739
She was dropped down
the laundry chute as a bab,
and I took her in

09:40.739 --> 09:41.872
out the goodness
of my heart,

09:41.872 --> 09:43.973
and I’ve done my best,
Mr. Wonka, honest, I have,

09:43.973 --> 09:46.547
but she’s been left
with a suspicious nature.

09:46.547 --> 09:49.143
She sees conspiracy
everywhere.

09:49.143 --> 09:51.046
Poor girl.
- I know.

09:51.046 --> 09:52.817
These are just
your standard Ts and Cs,

09:52.817 --> 09:57.052
but you’re welcome
to take a look if you want.

09:57.052 --> 09:59.054
I’ll just give it a once-over.

10:06.831 --> 10:09.669
Well, that all seems
to be in order.

10:09.669 --> 10:10.703
- Really?
- Uh-huh.

10:10.703 --> 10:12.672
Hello.
- Ah!

10:12.672 --> 10:14.476
Then welcome to Scrubitt’s.

10:16.038 --> 10:19.415
There you are, Mr. Wonka.
The entrepreneurial suite.

10:19.415 --> 10:22.517
There’s your four-poster,
and your sink plus soap,

10:22.517 --> 10:24.046
and there’s a little mint
on your pillow.

10:24.046 --> 10:25.685
Fantastic.

10:25.685 --> 10:27.852
What kind people.

10:35.563 --> 10:37.730
Noodle!

10:38.192 --> 10:39.765
Oh, Noodle!

10:39.765 --> 10:40.865
Yes, Mrs. Scrubitt?

10:40.865 --> 10:42.702
I’ve been lookin’ for you.

10:42.702 --> 10:43.736
What do you want?

10:43.736 --> 10:45.771
I wanna teach you a lesson,
you miserable little bookworm.

10:45.771 --> 10:46.706
What did I do wrong?

10:46.706 --> 10:47.971
You know what you did,
you brat.

10:47.971 --> 10:49.940
- Stop squirming!
- What? No, please.

10:50.743 --> 10:52.613
You ever
interfere in my business again,

10:52.613 --> 10:55.583
and you’ll be
in this coop all week.
Do you understand?

10:55.583 --> 10:58.685
Yes, Mrs. Scrubitt.
Sorry, Mrs. Scrubitt.

10:58.685 --> 11:02.183
I should think so, too.

11:30.244 --> 11:33.082
Here we go, Mamma.

11:38.626 --> 11:42.630
Ladies and gentlemen
of the Galeries Gourmet,

11:42.630 --> 11:44.093
my name is Willy Wonka,

11:44.093 --> 11:47.503
and I have come to show you
a marvelous morsel,

11:47.503 --> 11:48.933
an incredible edible,

11:48.933 --> 11:51.639
an unbeatable eatable,

11:51.639 --> 11:53.839
the likes of which
this world has never seen.

11:53.839 --> 11:56.644
So quiet up and listen down.

11:56.644 --> 11:58.844
No, scratch that, reverse it.

11:58.844 --> 12:00.747
I give to you

12:00.747 --> 12:01.583
the Hoverchoc.

12:07.787 --> 12:09.184
♪ In a ♪

12:09.184 --> 12:10.856
♪ Jungle near Mumbai ♪

12:10.856 --> 12:12.825
- ♪ There’s a little hoverfly ♪

12:12.825 --> 12:15.927
♪ Whose wings go
At a thousand flaps a sec ♪

12:15.927 --> 12:17.159
♪ And that’s no lie ♪

12:17.159 --> 12:18.963
♪ These microscopic fleas ♪

12:18.963 --> 12:20.899
♪ Like chocolate
More than leaves ♪

12:20.899 --> 12:22.967
♪ And when asked nicely,
Lay precisely ♪

12:22.967 --> 12:25.805
♪ One little egg
In each of these ♪

12:26.641 --> 12:28.742
♪ When it hatches
From its shell ♪

12:28.742 --> 12:30.304
♪ It gives a happy yell
Whoo-hoo!♪

12:30.304 --> 12:34.176
♪ How thrilling to be living
In a chocolate hotel ♪

12:34.176 --> 12:38.917
♪ It beats its wings with glee
And then, as you will see ♪

12:38.917 --> 12:40.182
♪ The chocolate will levitate ♪

12:40.182 --> 12:45.594
♪ And float most gracefully ♪

12:45.891 --> 12:50.159
- ♪ Well, there’s chocolate ♪

12:50.159 --> 12:51.963
♪ And there’s chocolate ♪

12:51.963 --> 12:54.702
♪ But only Wonka’s
Makes your eyes ♪

12:54.702 --> 12:56.968
♪ Pop out their socke-lets ♪

12:56.968 --> 12:59.267
♪ Put your hand
Into your pocke-let ♪

12:59.267 --> 13:01.775
♪ Get yourself
Some Wonka chocolate ♪

13:01.775 --> 13:05.713
♪ Come now
I insist ♪

13:05.713 --> 13:08.881
♪ You’ve never
Had chocolate like this ♪

13:08.881 --> 13:13.952
♪ No, you’ve never
Had chocolate like this ♪

13:15.690 --> 13:16.317
Bravo!

13:16.317 --> 13:19.694
-  Bravo!

13:20.222 --> 13:21.124
Thank you.

13:21.124 --> 13:23.995
- Miss Bon-Bon?
- Yes, Mr. Slugworth.

13:23.995 --> 13:24.963
Call the police.

13:24.963 --> 13:26.228
Very good, sir.

13:26.228 --> 13:28.802
Well, who wants to try one?

13:28.802 --> 13:31.101
-  Me, please!
-  I will.

13:32.135 --> 13:34.775
Mr. Slugworth, sir.
-  ’Scuse me.

13:34.775 --> 13:35.842
Mr. Fickelgruber.

13:35.842 --> 13:38.240
- And Mr. Prodnose.

13:38.240 --> 13:39.076
What an honor.

13:39.076 --> 13:40.341
Ever since
I was a little boy...

13:40.341 --> 13:42.618
- That is quite a handshake.

13:42.618 --> 13:45.049
It’s a business handshake,
Mr. Wonka.

13:45.049 --> 13:47.854
Lets people know
I mean business.

13:47.854 --> 13:48.954
- Huh...
- Now, come along.

13:48.954 --> 13:54.124
Let’s try one of these
so-called Hoverchocs.

14:03.298 --> 14:04.739
Ooh.

14:04.739 --> 14:06.873
It’s not just chocolate,
is it?

14:06.873 --> 14:08.270
There’s...

14:08.270 --> 14:09.975
- marshmallow.
-  That’s right.

14:09.975 --> 14:12.406
Harvested from
the mallow marshes of Peru.

14:12.406 --> 14:14.408
And caramel.

14:14.408 --> 14:16.377
But... but it’s...
-  Salted.

14:16.377 --> 14:19.413
With the bittersweet tears
of a Russian clown.

14:19.413 --> 14:22.086
-  And is that...

14:22.086 --> 14:23.824
Surely not?

14:23.890 --> 14:24.352
Cherry?

14:24.352 --> 14:26.156
Cherry-picked by
the pick of the cherry pickers

14:26.156 --> 14:28.125
from the Imperial Gardens
in Japan.

14:28.125 --> 14:31.392
- Well, Mr. Wonka.

14:31.392 --> 14:33.900
I’ve been in this business
a very long time,

14:33.900 --> 14:34.901
and I can safely say

14:34.901 --> 14:38.135
that of all the chocolate
I have ever tasted,

14:38.135 --> 14:40.203
this is without doubt

14:40.203 --> 14:43.371
the absolute 100% worst.

14:43.371 --> 14:44.405
- Whoo!

14:44.405 --> 14:46.011
There we have it,
ladies and gentlemen.

14:46.011 --> 14:48.244
An endorsement from Mr...

14:48.244 --> 14:49.047
Wait. The worst?

14:49.047 --> 14:52.017
We three
are the fiercest of rivals,

14:52.017 --> 14:53.381
and yet we agree on one thing.

14:53.381 --> 14:55.988
A good chocolate
should be simple.

14:55.988 --> 14:57.385
Plain. Uncomplicated.

14:57.385 --> 15:01.059
Whereas this, with all
its bells and whistles...

15:01.059 --> 15:03.457
Well, it’s just...

15:03.457 --> 15:05.195
Weird.

15:05.393 --> 15:06.394
That’s a shame.

15:06.394 --> 15:09.969
- If you thought
the chocolate was weird,

15:09.969 --> 15:12.774
you’re gonna hate
what happens next.

15:12.840 --> 15:14.237
- Hmm?

15:14.237 --> 15:16.074
What’s happening?
Whoa, what’s going on?

15:16.074 --> 15:18.076
That’s the hoverfly.

15:18.076 --> 15:19.880
It’s broken
out of its cocoon.

15:19.880 --> 15:22.014
It’s flapping its wings
like billy-oh.

15:23.114 --> 15:25.919
My hair!
You mean a fly is doing this?

15:25.919 --> 15:27.052
Yes. But don’t worry.

15:27.052 --> 15:29.153
It’ll be completely unharmed.
- Oh, thank you.

15:29.153 --> 15:31.122
In about 20 minutes,
it’ll get tired

15:31.122 --> 15:33.091
and exit through your rear.

15:33.091 --> 15:33.894
You what?

15:33.894 --> 15:35.995
He means we’re going to
fart them out of our botties!

15:35.995 --> 15:37.766
Yes, I know what he meant.

15:37.766 --> 15:39.229
You’re off your rocker, Wonka!

15:39.229 --> 15:40.164
Who in their right mind

15:40.164 --> 15:41.770
wants a chocolate
that makes you fly?

15:41.770 --> 15:43.464
Well, let’s find out,
shall we?

15:43.464 --> 15:44.839
Who’s for a Hoverchoc?

15:44.839 --> 15:47.138
-  I want one!

15:47.138 --> 15:50.042
One sovereign, please.
Thank you.

15:50.042 --> 15:51.307
Thank you very much.

15:51.307 --> 15:53.749
One sovereign.
Thank you, madam.

15:53.749 --> 15:55.146
Enjoy your flight.

15:55.916 --> 15:58.886
Look, I’m flying!
I’m flying!

16:01.218 --> 16:03.759
How’s the view
up there?

16:03.825 --> 16:07.224
Not too high, darling!

16:09.325 --> 16:10.260
Beat it, kid.

16:10.260 --> 16:12.328
All right, folks.
Nothin’ to see here.

16:12.328 --> 16:16.904
Just a small group of people
defyin’ the laws of gravity.

16:16.904 --> 16:17.971
- Yeah.
- Hook ’em, boys.

16:17.971 --> 16:19.533
That’s the Hoverchoc,
sir. That’s the point.

16:19.533 --> 16:22.943
I’m afraid
we’ve had some complaints
about you, sir.

16:22.943 --> 16:23.878
Complaints?

16:23.878 --> 16:25.946
That you’re disrupting
the trade of other businesses.

16:25.946 --> 16:28.443
I’m regrettably obliged
to move you on

16:28.443 --> 16:29.950
and to confiscate

16:29.950 --> 16:31.083
- your earnings.

16:31.083 --> 16:32.887
Hey!
What are you doing?
-  No!

16:32.887 --> 16:34.383
Don’t worry,
it’s going to a good cause.

16:34.383 --> 16:36.418
-  Get off.
- Sick kids, or something.

16:36.418 --> 16:38.057
Sorry, sir. Rules is rules.

16:38.057 --> 16:39.487
Cheeky devil, you!
Come here!

16:39.487 --> 16:42.831
Could you at least
leave me a sovereign?

16:42.831 --> 16:45.130
I need to pay for my room.

16:47.297 --> 16:50.531
- Here.

16:51.235 --> 16:52.940
Thank you.

16:55.470 --> 16:58.077
Evening, Mr. Wonka.

16:58.374 --> 16:59.177
How’d it go?

16:59.177 --> 17:00.442
Not quite as well
as I’d hoped.

17:00.442 --> 17:03.885
Oh, shame. Well, I’m afraid
we do have to settle up now.

17:03.885 --> 17:07.086
Well, thankfully,
the room’s taken care of.

17:07.086 --> 17:08.923
Believe we said a sovereign.

17:08.923 --> 17:09.825
For the room, yes.

17:09.825 --> 17:12.355
But you have incurred
a few extras

17:12.355 --> 17:16.161
during the course of your
residency with ourselves.

17:16.161 --> 17:19.131
- Have I?
- Yes, you have.

17:19.131 --> 17:22.431
There was that glass of gin
you had on arrival,

17:22.431 --> 17:23.597
and if I remember rightly,

17:23.597 --> 17:26.336
you warmed your cockles
by the fire.

17:26.336 --> 17:27.502
He did indeed, Mrs. Scrubitt.

17:27.502 --> 17:30.175
- Cockle-warming is extra, see?

17:30.175 --> 17:32.441
Used the stairs
to get to his room, and all.

17:32.441 --> 17:34.377
Oh, then
you’ve got your stair charge,

17:34.377 --> 17:37.886
and that is per step,
I’m afraid. Up and down.

17:37.886 --> 17:39.019
Now, tell me, Mr. Wonka,

17:39.019 --> 17:41.890
did you happen
to use the mini bar?

17:41.890 --> 17:43.023
There’s a minibar?

17:43.023 --> 17:44.255
Mini bar of soap.

17:44.255 --> 17:45.091
By the sink.

17:45.091 --> 17:46.961
Uh... I might have, briefly.
- Oh-ho!

17:46.961 --> 17:49.392
See? Even Bleacher knows
you never touch the mini bar,

17:49.392 --> 17:51.900
and he was raised in a ditch.

17:51.900 --> 17:53.231
Add in your mattress hire,

17:53.231 --> 17:55.332
your linen lease,
and your pillow penalty,

17:55.332 --> 17:57.499
and you are looking at...

17:57.499 --> 17:59.138
Ten thousand sovereigns.

17:59.138 --> 18:00.304
You gotta be kidding me?

18:00.304 --> 18:02.878
It’s all in the small print, dearie.

18:02.878 --> 18:04.572
I don’t have
10,000 sovereigns.

18:05.540 --> 18:07.311
Then we have a problem,
Mr. Wonka.

18:07.311 --> 18:08.576
You’re gonna
have to work it off

18:08.576 --> 18:10.886
in the Wash House, ain’t ya?

18:10.886 --> 18:12.217
At a sovereign a day.

18:12.217 --> 18:13.185
Ten thousand days is...

18:13.185 --> 18:14.450
Twenty-seven years.

18:14.450 --> 18:15.616
- Hey!
-  Four months.

18:15.616 --> 18:17.057
And 16 days.

18:22.623 --> 18:24.493
-  Ah.

18:24.493 --> 18:27.562
You must be
Mr. Wonka.
- Who are you?

18:27.562 --> 18:31.434
Abacus Crunch,
chartered accountant.

18:31.434 --> 18:32.468
At least, I was.

18:32.468 --> 18:34.305
- Now, uh...
- He runs the place.

18:34.305 --> 18:37.242
And you best do as he says,
or you’ll answer to me.

18:37.242 --> 18:39.046
Piper Benz. Plumber by trade.

18:39.046 --> 18:41.609
This is
Miss Lottie Bell.

18:41.609 --> 18:43.116
Hi.

18:43.116 --> 18:44.051
She don’t talk much.

18:44.051 --> 18:48.484
And I’m Larry Chucklesworth!

18:48.484 --> 18:49.419
Comedian.

18:49.419 --> 18:50.255
Hmm.

18:50.255 --> 18:52.224
So they got all of you, too,
did they?

18:52.224 --> 18:53.324
I’m afraid so.

18:53.324 --> 18:54.589
We each of us found ourselves

18:54.589 --> 18:56.030
in need of a cheap place
to stay,

18:56.030 --> 18:58.362
and neglected
to read the small print.

18:58.362 --> 19:02.663
One moment of stupidity,
followed by endless regret.

19:02.663 --> 19:06.634
Sounds like my third marriage.

19:06.700 --> 19:08.471
I’m sorry, I do that a lot.

19:08.471 --> 19:09.604
He does.
- A lot.

19:09.604 --> 19:11.573
I’ve only
been married once,

19:11.573 --> 19:12.640
and it didn’t work out.

19:12.640 --> 19:14.312
There’s gotta be
some way outta here.

19:14.312 --> 19:15.577
You don’t think
we’ve tried?

19:15.577 --> 19:18.052
There are bars on the window
and there’s a dog on the door.

19:18.052 --> 19:19.680
And even
if you could get out,

19:19.680 --> 19:20.956
that contract is watertight.

19:20.956 --> 19:24.388
If you’re not here
at roll call, Mrs. Scrubitt
will call the police,

19:24.388 --> 19:25.488
they’ll bring you right back,

19:25.488 --> 19:28.029
and she’ll charge you
a thousand
for the inconvenience.

19:28.689 --> 19:30.361
All right, everybody.
Back to work.

19:30.361 --> 19:31.560
- Come along, Mr. Wonka.

19:31.560 --> 19:34.596
- You come with me.

19:34.596 --> 19:38.171
You’re in here. On suds.

19:43.605 --> 19:44.309
Whoa.

19:44.309 --> 19:46.509
♪ First, you pick up
The apparel ♪

19:46.509 --> 19:48.984
♪ And you stick it
In a barrel ♪

19:48.984 --> 19:51.085
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

19:51.382 --> 19:57.025
♪ Then you take
It to the mangle
And you turn a giant handle ♪

19:57.025 --> 19:59.159
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

20:00.094 --> 20:04.659
♪ Then it’s hung up really high
Until it’s nearly dry ♪

20:04.659 --> 20:06.529
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

20:08.531 --> 20:13.074
♪ But when we sing this song
The day don’t seem so long ♪

20:13.074 --> 20:14.768
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

20:14.768 --> 20:17.540
It’s still long, though.

20:23.447 --> 20:25.185
♪ Gotta press out
All the creases ♪

20:25.185 --> 20:27.154
♪ From the dresses
And chemises ♪

20:27.154 --> 20:28.749
♪ Rub, rub ♪

20:30.388 --> 20:32.753
♪ Gotta fold ’em
Like they told us ♪

20:32.753 --> 20:34.095
♪ Or they’ll scold us ♪

20:34.095 --> 20:36.526
♪ And withhold our grub, grub ♪

20:38.066 --> 20:42.631
♪ We all signed the dotted line
So we gotta do our time ♪

20:42.631 --> 20:46.602
- ♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

20:46.602 --> 20:49.704
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

20:49.704 --> 20:52.344
And if you don’t agree...

20:52.344 --> 20:53.510
See clause five.

20:53.510 --> 20:57.151
- Section 7A.
- Paragraph 22.

20:57.151 --> 20:58.284
Part D.

20:58.284 --> 20:59.714
Which says...

20:59.714 --> 21:00.814
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

21:04.092 --> 21:05.687
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

21:07.821 --> 21:11.132
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

21:12.397 --> 21:14.696
♪ Scrub, scrub ♪

21:39.094 --> 21:42.328
-  Room service.

21:42.427 --> 21:45.166
Told you to read
the small print.

21:45.463 --> 21:47.663
Slight problem with that.

21:48.466 --> 21:50.204
You can’t read, can you?

21:50.204 --> 21:54.406
I focused my studies
almost exclusively
on chocolate.

21:54.406 --> 21:55.374
I see.

21:55.374 --> 21:58.245
For everything else,
I’ve relied on the kindness
of strangers.

21:58.245 --> 22:02.843
And look
where that’s got you.
The staff quarters.

22:03.184 --> 22:04.746
You’ve got a bed.

22:07.254 --> 22:09.124
You had a bed.

22:09.124 --> 22:13.293
Desk, and a wash basin/toilet.

22:13.293 --> 22:14.327
- Ugh.
- The water comes

22:14.327 --> 22:17.594
in two temperatures. Cold...

22:17.594 --> 22:19.530
...and colder.

22:20.267 --> 22:22.236
How much do you owe them?

22:22.236 --> 22:23.270
Ten thousand.

22:23.270 --> 22:25.734
Count yourself lucky.
I owe 30.

22:25.734 --> 22:27.604
What? How do you
owe them money?

22:27.604 --> 22:30.442
I thought they found you
down a laundry chute.

22:30.442 --> 22:31.311
Oh, they did.

22:31.311 --> 22:33.148
Took me in out of the goodness
of their hearts

22:33.148 --> 22:35.744
and charged me
for the privilege.

22:35.744 --> 22:36.778
What a pair of monsters.

22:36.778 --> 22:40.320
The greedy beat the needy
every time, Mr. Wonka.

22:40.320 --> 22:42.322
Guess it’s just
the way of the world.

22:42.322 --> 22:43.521
Oh, come on, Noodle.

22:43.521 --> 22:46.755
That’s just your
Orphan Syndrome talking.

22:46.755 --> 22:48.823
- My what?
- Your Orphan Syndrome.

22:48.823 --> 22:52.695
And we are not gonna
be eating any slops.

22:52.695 --> 22:54.235
What are you doing?

22:54.235 --> 22:55.863
I’m making chocolate,
o’ course.

22:55.863 --> 22:56.897
How do you like it? Dark?

22:56.897 --> 23:00.208
White? Nutty?
Absolutely insane?

23:00.208 --> 23:01.407
I don’t know.

23:01.407 --> 23:03.838
I’ve never had any.

23:03.838 --> 23:06.907
You’ve never had chocolate?

23:06.907 --> 23:08.513
- No.
-  What?

23:08.513 --> 23:10.779
You’ve never had chocolate?

23:10.878 --> 23:11.780
Still no.

23:11.780 --> 23:14.651
Well, this is unbelievable.
I mean, this is outrageous.

23:14.651 --> 23:16.884
Well, lucky for you, Noodle,
I have a selection

23:16.884 --> 23:18.523
of the world’s
finest ingredients

23:18.523 --> 23:20.624
right here
in my travel factory.

23:26.234 --> 23:26.762
Whoa.

23:26.762 --> 23:29.435
Where to begin?
That’s the question.

23:29.435 --> 23:30.667
I know!

23:30.667 --> 23:31.470
Silver Linings.

23:31.470 --> 23:34.638
Made of condensed
thunder clouds

23:34.770 --> 23:36.673
and liquid sunlight.

23:36.673 --> 23:39.313
Helps you see
that faint ray o’ hope

23:39.313 --> 23:41.447
beyond the shadow of despair.

23:41.447 --> 23:42.349
Just what we need,

23:42.349 --> 23:43.746
- wouldn’t you say?

23:43.746 --> 23:45.748
Did you always
wanna make chocolate?

23:45.748 --> 23:47.651
No.

23:47.651 --> 23:49.290
Back when I was your age,

23:49.290 --> 23:51.358
I wanted to be a magician.

23:51.358 --> 23:53.327
My mom was a cook.

23:53.327 --> 23:55.791
We lived on the river,
just the two of us.

23:55.791 --> 24:00.235
In a perfect little
world of our own.

24:00.994 --> 24:03.271
The way I remember it,
I used to spend

24:03.271 --> 24:04.734
every waking hour
trying to come up

24:04.734 --> 24:08.540
with some new trick
to impress my mom.

24:08.837 --> 24:10.575
Bravo!

24:10.575 --> 24:14.480
But the real magic
came from her.

24:14.975 --> 24:17.945
We didn’t have a lotta money,
but each week,

24:17.945 --> 24:19.881
she brought home
one cocoa bean.

24:19.881 --> 24:21.619
And by the time my birthday
came around,

24:21.619 --> 24:25.623
there was enough to make
a single bar o’ chocolate.

24:25.623 --> 24:28.923
But it wasn’t
just any old chocolate.

24:28.923 --> 24:30.694
Far from it.

24:30.694 --> 24:33.763
This has to be
the best chocolate
in the world.

24:33.763 --> 24:35.369
Oh,
don’t know about that.

24:35.369 --> 24:37.998
They say the very best
comes from a place

24:37.998 --> 24:39.703
called the Galeries Gourmet.

24:39.703 --> 24:43.344
Theirs can’t be any better
than yours, Mamma.

24:43.344 --> 24:44.642
It’s impossible.

24:44.642 --> 24:47.810
Well, as it so happens,

24:47.810 --> 24:49.416
I do know a little secret

24:49.416 --> 24:52.848
that even
those fancy-pants don’t.

24:53.354 --> 24:54.388
What is it?

24:54.388 --> 24:55.015
I’ll tell ya.

24:55.015 --> 24:59.426
When you’re older.
Now get to sleep.

25:05.025 --> 25:06.664
We should go, Amma.

25:06.664 --> 25:07.896
Where’s that, then?

25:07.896 --> 25:10.063
To the Galeries Gourmet.
- What?

25:10.063 --> 25:11.801
And start a shop?
- Yeah.

25:11.801 --> 25:14.705
With our name above the door
and everything.

25:14.705 --> 25:17.840
That’s a wonderful dream, honey.

25:17.906 --> 25:20.546
Is that all it is?

25:21.008 --> 25:23.384
Just a dream?

25:24.418 --> 25:25.914
Hey now.

25:27.487 --> 25:32.492
Every good thing in this world
started with a dream.

25:32.492 --> 25:33.955
So you hold on to yours.

25:33.955 --> 25:36.694
And when you do share
chocolate with the world,

25:36.694 --> 25:40.863
oh, I’ll be right there
beside ya.

25:40.863 --> 25:41.600
Promise?

25:41.600 --> 25:42.700
Do better than that.

25:42.700 --> 25:45.967
I pinkie promise.

25:47.606 --> 25:48.871
Now,

25:48.871 --> 25:50.510
sleep.

25:52.413 --> 25:55.845
So, what was it, Willy?

25:55.845 --> 25:57.847
What was the secret?

25:57.847 --> 26:00.487
I never found out.

26:00.817 --> 26:02.918
Soon after, she fell sick.

26:02.918 --> 26:08.429
And before I knew it,
all I had left
was her bar of chocolate.

26:12.026 --> 26:13.896
That’s why I’m here, Noodle.

26:13.896 --> 26:17.504
So I can feel the same way
I did back then,

26:17.504 --> 26:20.067
eating chocolate with her.

26:20.903 --> 26:21.838
What do you mean?

26:21.838 --> 26:24.874
My mom once promised
that when I share chocolate
with the world,

26:24.874 --> 26:27.107
she’d be right there
beside me.

26:28.416 --> 26:30.748
I know it sounds crazy,
but I always hoped

26:30.748 --> 26:33.146
she’d somehow
keep that promise.

26:34.015 --> 26:37.425
She might even
tell me her secret.

26:42.925 --> 26:45.125
Here. Try one.

27:02.813 --> 27:04.947
Wish you hadn’t done that.

27:04.947 --> 27:07.818
You don’t like it?
- No,

27:07.818 --> 27:11.052
I like it. It’s just...

27:11.184 --> 27:12.053
What?

27:12.053 --> 27:16.431
Now each day
I don’t have chocolate
will be a little harder.

27:16.431 --> 27:21.161
Then how would you like
to have all the chocolate
you can eat, every day,

27:21.161 --> 27:22.833
for the rest of your life?

27:22.833 --> 27:23.999
A lifetime supply?

27:23.999 --> 27:26.441
A lifetime supply.

27:26.441 --> 27:27.167
What would I have to do?

27:27.167 --> 27:29.004
Not much.
Just get me out of here.

27:29.004 --> 27:30.676
Are you crazy?
- Shh!

27:30.676 --> 27:32.612
It’s easy. I’ll get someone
to cover my shift,

27:32.612 --> 27:34.449
and you could smuggle me out
in your laundry cart.

27:34.449 --> 27:35.813
- But I...
- Just for a few hours, mind.

27:35.813 --> 27:37.749
No one will even know
I was gone.

27:37.749 --> 27:38.849
What’s the point of that?

27:38.849 --> 27:40.917
To sell chocolate, o’ course!
We’ll split the profits

27:40.917 --> 27:42.721
and pay off Mrs. Scrubitt
in no time.

27:42.721 --> 27:43.656
It’s a nice idea, Willy.

27:43.656 --> 27:45.757
- It’s a great idea.
- But it’ll never work.

27:45.757 --> 27:47.726
’Course it will.
Eat your chocolate.

27:47.726 --> 27:48.859
You don’t understand.

27:48.859 --> 27:51.829
Mrs. Scrubitt’s like a hawk.
She keeps her beady eye
on everything

27:51.829 --> 27:55.767
that comes in and out
of the Wash House except...

27:56.196 --> 27:57.802
Huh.

27:57.868 --> 27:59.540
What is it?

27:59.540 --> 28:01.003
No, it’s nothing.

28:01.003 --> 28:02.807
Oh, okay.

28:02.906 --> 28:03.577
Huh.

28:03.577 --> 28:04.842
Double-huh!
That’s not nothing.

28:04.842 --> 28:06.547
That’s the Silver Lining.
It’s given you an idea.

28:06.547 --> 28:09.044
Okay. So, the one time
she dropped her guard

28:09.044 --> 28:11.112
was when this aristocrat
came to the laundry.

28:11.112 --> 28:13.114
He was only
asking for directions,

28:13.114 --> 28:15.721
but she was all over him
like a rash.

28:15.721 --> 28:17.085
It was disgusting.

28:17.085 --> 28:17.987
That’s it, Noodle.

28:17.987 --> 28:19.626
All we have to do
is find an aristocrat

28:19.626 --> 28:21.958
and slip out
while she’s distracted.

28:21.958 --> 28:22.992
Yeah, but...

28:22.992 --> 28:26.567
where are we going
to find an aristocrat?

28:29.031 --> 28:30.098
Huh.

28:30.098 --> 28:31.704
Huh?

28:32.100 --> 28:33.035
Huh.

28:33.035 --> 28:33.871
A double-huh.

28:33.871 --> 28:35.235
Do you have
a pencil and paper?

28:35.235 --> 28:38.744
- Uh-huh.
- I got an idea.

28:57.125 --> 28:59.699
I’ve come
to make a confession.

29:01.569 --> 29:05.034
You sound great, fellas.
Keep it up.

29:08.807 --> 29:12.305
Forgive me, Father,
for I have sinned.

29:12.877 --> 29:17.816
I have had 150 of these
since my last confession.

29:19.279 --> 29:23.118
Temptation is very hard
to resist.

29:26.022 --> 29:27.661
Mmm.

29:27.661 --> 29:29.828
Send me down.

29:29.927 --> 29:33.568
- I’ll see you later.

29:37.836 --> 29:40.575
Good evening, Chief.

29:40.674 --> 29:41.741
They’re all waiting.

29:41.741 --> 29:43.809
Thank you very much.

29:44.744 --> 29:47.208
Good evening, gentlemen.
I’ve brought my invoice.

29:47.208 --> 29:51.850
One chocolatier moved on
for the usual fee.

29:51.850 --> 29:53.148
Oh.

29:53.148 --> 29:54.281
Here we go, baby.

29:54.281 --> 29:55.656
There’s the good stuff. Yeah.

29:55.656 --> 29:57.284
Tell me, Chief...
Mm-hmm?

29:57.284 --> 30:00.089
...how would you like
to earn a few more of those?

30:00.089 --> 30:01.123
Oh, I am listening.

30:01.123 --> 30:02.729
We think
that Mr. Wonka

30:02.729 --> 30:07.063
might require a little more
than simply moving on.

30:07.063 --> 30:09.032
- Oh.
-  He’s good.

30:09.032 --> 30:10.165
Too good.

30:10.165 --> 30:11.001
And what’s more,

30:11.001 --> 30:13.234
he only charges
a sovereign a chocolate.

30:13.234 --> 30:17.139
So anyone can afford them,
even the...

30:18.272 --> 30:19.746
You know, the...

30:19.746 --> 30:22.012
- The poor?
-  Oh, dear.

30:22.012 --> 30:25.048
I’ve just been
a little bit sick in my mouth.

30:25.048 --> 30:26.819
Could you please refrain
from mentioning

30:26.819 --> 30:28.249
that demographic
in my presence?

30:28.249 --> 30:30.152
He doesn’t like it
when people say "poor."

30:30.152 --> 30:31.923
-  Sorry, Felix.

30:31.923 --> 30:35.091
We want you to send
Wonka a message.

30:35.091 --> 30:36.697
Backed up by physical force.

30:36.697 --> 30:39.667
That if he attempts to sell
chocolate in this town again,

30:39.667 --> 30:43.704
he is liable to meet
with a little accident.

30:43.704 --> 30:45.970
In which he dies.

30:45.970 --> 30:47.367
Yeah, no, I...
I got that already.

30:47.367 --> 30:48.841
You don’t have
to keep saying it.

30:48.841 --> 30:50.975
I’m just making sure
we’re all on the same page.

30:50.975 --> 30:52.042
Well, no one’s on your page.

30:52.042 --> 30:54.011
What’s that supposed to mean?
Well, I know what it means...

30:54.011 --> 30:55.078
Actually, what does it mean?

30:55.078 --> 30:57.311
Gentlemen, please.

30:58.015 --> 30:59.984
So, what do you say, Chief?

30:59.984 --> 31:00.886
Do we have a deal?

31:00.886 --> 31:03.790
Well, listen, fellas,
I’m an officer of the law.

31:03.790 --> 31:08.322
I can’t just go around
roughin’ up your competition.

31:08.960 --> 31:10.665
I’m sorry.

31:10.896 --> 31:11.699
Well now, Chief.

31:13.800 --> 31:16.704
I can see that
you’re a man of integrity.

31:18.937 --> 31:19.839
Thank you.

31:19.839 --> 31:22.369
But ask yourself this...

31:23.436 --> 31:26.307
♪ Have you got a sweet tooth?♪

31:26.307 --> 31:27.110
♪ I do ♪

