to be doing this.

48:11.146 --> 48:12.950
But I still gotta
give ya a message.

48:12.950 --> 48:14.919
Sell chocolate
in this town again,

48:14.919 --> 48:17.724
you’re gonna get more
than a bonk on the head.

48:17.724 --> 48:19.726
I don’t have
a bonk on the head.

48:21.354 --> 48:23.356
What is with me today? I...

48:23.356 --> 48:26.227
Can you give me
just a second?
- Sure.

48:28.460 --> 48:29.901
Lord Bleachowitz.

48:29.901 --> 48:34.741
Mrs. Scrubitt.
Your eyes are like
two rabbit droppings

48:34.741 --> 48:35.709
in a couple of bowls

48:35.709 --> 48:36.842
- of custard.
- Oh!

48:36.842 --> 48:38.811
You really do have a way
with words.

48:38.811 --> 48:41.176
See you downstairs.

48:41.176 --> 48:43.013
Geronimo!

48:43.013 --> 48:44.718
Ah, Mr. Wonka.

48:44.718 --> 48:46.115
Good of you to join us.

48:46.115 --> 48:48.788
Not late, am I?
-  Well, no.

48:48.788 --> 48:50.053
Cutting it a bit fine, but...

48:50.053 --> 48:51.384
Has Tiddles been
pulling his weight?

48:51.384 --> 48:52.957
- As a matter of fact,

48:52.957 --> 48:54.090
Tiddles has been
a very good boy,

48:54.090 --> 48:56.092
and productivity is up 30%.

48:56.092 --> 48:57.489
We took
the afternoon off.

48:57.489 --> 48:59.227
But that’s not the point.

48:59.227 --> 49:00.426
This is the point.

49:00.426 --> 49:01.966
Not now, Larry.
- Sorry.

49:01.966 --> 49:03.737
The point is...

49:03.737 --> 49:04.463
Where have you been?

49:04.463 --> 49:07.367
And why do you smell
of giraffe?

49:07.367 --> 49:08.973
Guess I owe you guys
an explanation.

49:08.973 --> 49:11.206
Mm.
The truth is,

49:11.206 --> 49:12.339
I’m a chocolate maker.

49:12.339 --> 49:15.243
Not just any chocolate.
The best in the world.

49:15.243 --> 49:18.884
Ah, well,
Noodle’s flattering me,
but she’s right.

49:18.884 --> 49:19.786
They’re exquisite.

49:19.786 --> 49:22.789
Plan is to sell chocolate
and pay off Mrs. Scrubitt.

49:22.789 --> 49:25.418
At least,
that was the plan, until...

49:25.418 --> 49:26.320
Oh, let me guess.

49:26.320 --> 49:30.192
You had a little run-in
with the Chief of Police?

49:30.192 --> 49:31.193
How do you know that?

49:31.193 --> 49:34.526
Because I was
Slugworth’s accountant.

49:34.526 --> 49:35.934
For a week, at least.

49:35.934 --> 49:37.529
His regular bookkeeper
was off sick.

49:37.529 --> 49:39.333
- Station, please.
-  And I was called

49:39.333 --> 49:42.270
halfway across the country
to take his place.

49:42.270 --> 49:44.008
Good evening, Mr. Slugworth.

49:44.008 --> 49:47.011
I just need
your signature on...

49:47.011 --> 49:49.442
Seemed a straightforward job.

49:49.442 --> 49:50.311
Oh.

49:50.311 --> 49:52.214
Until I realized

49:52.214 --> 49:54.920
there were two sets of books.

49:54.920 --> 49:56.955
One for the authorities,

49:56.955 --> 49:59.551
and one which told the truth.

49:59.551 --> 50:03.423
Slugworth, Fickelgruber,
and Prodnose

50:03.423 --> 50:05.293
have been in cahoots
for years.

50:05.293 --> 50:08.065
A sort of chocolate cartel,
if you will.

50:08.065 --> 50:10.265
They’ve been watering down
their chocolate

50:10.265 --> 50:13.400
and storing the excess
in a secret vault

50:13.400 --> 50:14.973
deep beneath the cathedral,

50:14.973 --> 50:18.240
guarded round the clock
by a corrupt cleric

50:18.240 --> 50:21.914
and 500 chocoholic monks.

50:21.914 --> 50:26.017
The only way in is down
a secret elevator, and past

50:26.017 --> 50:28.382
the Mistress of the Keys.

50:28.382 --> 50:30.417
A subterranean sentinel...

50:30.417 --> 50:32.826
...who hasn’t seen
sunlight in years.

50:32.826 --> 50:34.223
Good evening.

50:34.223 --> 50:36.060
There’s thousands
of gallons of chocolate

50:36.060 --> 50:39.426
down there, and the Cartel
use it to bribe,

50:39.426 --> 50:42.132
blackmail, and bludgeon
the competition.

50:42.132 --> 50:44.838
I do not care that
they were school children...

50:44.838 --> 50:48.237
...they were in our way.
Next time, put your foot down.

50:48.237 --> 50:49.073
Miss Bon-Bon?

50:49.073 --> 50:50.503
Good morning, Mr. Slugworth.

50:50.503 --> 50:53.572
From now on, I’ll be keeping
the ledger in the vault.

50:53.572 --> 50:55.882
Very good, sir.

50:56.509 --> 50:58.412
Oh, and Mr. Crunch?

50:59.611 --> 51:00.513
Yes?

51:00.513 --> 51:02.548
You’re fired.

51:04.154 --> 51:05.892
Very good, sir.

51:06.321 --> 51:07.894
I’m sorry, Mr. Wonka,

51:07.894 --> 51:10.963
but they’ve got you
right where they want you.

51:10.963 --> 51:13.625
You can’t get a shop
without selling chocolate,

51:13.625 --> 51:18.069
and you can’t sell chocolate
without a shop.

51:20.874 --> 51:22.469
Hey, Noodle!

51:22.469 --> 51:24.240
Noodle! Psst!

51:25.472 --> 51:27.045
What is it, Willy?

51:27.045 --> 51:28.310
Watch out.

51:28.310 --> 51:29.608
Whoa!

51:34.646 --> 51:35.614
What’s this for?

51:35.614 --> 51:39.585
Your wages.
A lifetime supply, remember?

51:39.585 --> 51:41.059
You didn’t have to do that.

51:41.059 --> 51:44.898
Of course I did.
I gave you my word.

51:45.030 --> 51:46.328
Well, thanks.

51:46.328 --> 51:50.299
I’ve got something
for you, too.
- For me?

51:55.634 --> 51:56.437
What’s this?

51:56.437 --> 51:59.506
Glass half full?
- Other way up.

51:59.506 --> 52:00.980
Glass half empty.

52:00.980 --> 52:03.510
It’s an "A."
Your first letter.

52:03.510 --> 52:05.985
I’m teaching you to read.

52:05.985 --> 52:06.579
Oh, Noodle.

52:06.579 --> 52:09.681
Well, I can’t have
my business partner
eaten by a tiger.

52:09.681 --> 52:11.419
Or nearly eaten.

52:11.419 --> 52:12.387
So we’re still partners?

52:12.387 --> 52:14.653
Sure, but I don’t know
how we’re gonna
sell any chocolate.

52:14.653 --> 52:19.328
Every time the police show up,
you’d have to vanish
into thin air.

52:19.328 --> 52:20.527
Like a magician.

52:20.527 --> 52:21.363
Right!

52:21.363 --> 52:23.365
Yeah, but it’s one thing
when you’re onstage.

52:23.365 --> 52:26.236
You have ropes and pulleys
and trapdoors.

52:26.236 --> 52:27.501
There’s none of those
on the street.

52:27.501 --> 52:29.503
As a matter of fact,
there are.

52:29.503 --> 52:32.110
There are trapdoors
all over the city.

52:32.110 --> 52:33.606
They’re called storm drains.

52:33.606 --> 52:35.113
I’d be happy
to show you around

52:35.113 --> 52:36.279
